        "hazard": "Fire weather (risk of wildfires)",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Outdoor workers|Frontline workers|Vulnerable health groups",
        "sectorsExposed": "Water supply|Agriculture|Forestry|Conservation",
        "impacts": "Moorland in the borough was drained in the past and so is at risk of wildfire during periods of drought when it dries out quickly. Fires may be started accidentally (e.g. discarded cigarette) or deliberately. Attending incidents puts fire service workers lives at risk, It puts properties on the edge of the moorland at risk and reduces air quality for residents, numbers dependent on wind direction. Fire destroys biodiversity and leaves the peat soils vulnerable to erosion. Large parts of the areas vulnerable to fire are used for water catchment. Eroding peat can affect water quality, which requires the water company to put additional resource in to cleaning up the contamination. Fire reduces grazing for sheep and affects cover for game birds.\\n\\nA Public Space Protection Order banning the building or lighting any kind of fire or barbeque, lighting fireworks or setting off sky lanterns has been introduced to try to reduce the incidence of accidental fires.\\n\\nRe-wetting the moor is the favoured solution to reduce fire risk and improve biodiversity. A local landowner is already in the process of restoring his area of moorland, Lancashire Peat Partnership has secured funds through the Nature for Climate Fund to extend the area of restoration and the Council has commissioned a restoration plan for the section of moor in its ownership. This work is expected to reduce the incidence and severity of future outbreaks of fire on the moors. A Landscape Recovery partnership - West Pennine More - has been established to bring all interested parties together to work collaboratively The Council is a member of the Partnership.",
