        "hazard": "River flooding",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Elderly|Women and girls|Outdoor workers|Other: Business and Industry|Children and youth|Vulnerable health groups|Indigenous peoples|Frontline workers",
        "sectorsExposed": "Human health and social work activities|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Administrative and support service activities|Water supply|Public administration and defence; compulsory social security",
        "impacts": "Fluvial flood risk has been identified as high for many areas of public service delivery including Business and Industry; Health, Communities and the Built Environment; Infrastructure; Natural Environment and Assets; \\nCCRA3 Technical Report outlines how future river and surface water climate change impacts are a major high level risk and that, despite progress with flood defences, risks are not being managed effectively with an adaptation shortfall which will further require government intervention. \\nThe assessment suggests:\u2022 Risks to people, communities and buildings include mortality, physical and mental health impacts, damage to property, financial implications of cleaning up or moving and disruption in terms of access to employment, education, health services and wider facilities.\u2022 Climate change will increase the number of properties at risk of flooding from all sources, and these could be in areas that have not previously been at risk of flooding.\u2022 Flood risk will be exacerbated and locked in unless building within the flood plain is avoided and properties developed in flood risk areas incorporate appropriate resilience measures and sustainable drainage systems designed for the lifespan of the development. The assessment suggests that although considerable advances have been made regarding the strategic management of flood risk at national and local levels, the risk magnitude remains high now and in the future in Wales, with more action needed due to the scale of the risk. Key areas of challenge relate to continued development on the flood plain, the management of surface water flooding via SuDS, the low take up of Property Flood Resilience (PFR), and the lack of UK-wide standards.\\nFluvial flooding has impacted many communities across CCR in 2024 and 2025 including most recently in June 2025, flash flooding impacting vulnerable communities in Bridgend https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cm2klpjp34mo and in 2024 impacting homes and businesses in Pontypridd https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cgj7qvj097po. NRW are coordinating 'catchment' response to address fluvial flooding and engaging all public bodies that operate within a catchment boundary. This regional approach is necessary to ensure that upstream actions don't have negative impacts further downstream. \\n",
