        "impacts": "Drought is becoming more of an issue across the CC Region. Welsh Governments adaptation strategy published in 2024 identified droughts are likely to be 86% more frequent with a global temperature increase of 20C.https://www.gov.wales/sites/default/files/publications/2024-10/climate-adaptation-strategy-for-wales-2024.pdf\\n\\nAlready in 2025, the UK and CCR are experiencing drought conditions, with the Met Office reporting that spring 2025 is set to be the warmest and driest in the UK for 50 years. https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cr4zwe7w422o#:~:text=Drought%20experts%20have%20issued%20stronger%20advice%20on%20water,upgraded%20from%20%22normal%22%20to%20%22prolonged%20dry%20weather%22%20status.\\n\\nWithin CCR, 54% of land is designated farmland, with drought (along with storms and flooding) directly impacting the agricultural community as well as potential water shortages for homes and other businesses. Water storage is a challenge, with Welsh Water in parts of Wales as of 12th June 2025, declaring 'Developing Drought' status for Mid & South Ceredigion due to the levels of water stored in the area's reservoirs. This currently does not directly impact the CCR region, however, Welsh Water are carefully monitoring in line with their drought response plan updated in 2025 https://www.dwrcymru.com/en/our-services/water/water-resources/draft-drought-plan-2025 \\n\\nhttps://naturalresourceswales.gov.uk/about-us/news-and-blogs/blogs/dry-weather-updates-2025/?lang=en\\n",
