        "vulnerableGroups": "Other: Farmers|Outdoor workers",
        "sectorsExposed": "Forestry|Agriculture",
        "impacts": "Loss of natural ground and soil, alongside soil degradation, erosion, and compaction is an issue for the city of Brighton & Hove. This includes the loss of soils to built environment / development and infrastructure pressures which leads to and exacerbates surface water flooding and over-heating issues as identified in the Climate Risk Vulnerability Assessment (2023). This is combined with impacts on the City Downland Estate (farmland etc), located in the South Downs National Park, which reduce farm productivity / food growing, causing land damage and biodiversity loss and likely impacts the city's water supply aquifer. These impacts affect the most vulnerable and the most deprived first and more significantly as reflected in the cost of living crisis with food costs escalating (2023 estimates c.\u00a3700-800 added to food bills) and the higher use of food banks as seen in the city and beyond. Land uses will be forced to change to adapt. This is addressed in The City Downland Estate Plan: https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/default/files/2023-02/7640%20City%20Downland%20Estate%20Plan%20phase4%20FINAL2.pdf. There is a risk to soil erosion from heavy rain events causing major erosion events, especially during the summer when a heavy rain event/storm happens after a period of dry weather. This could lead to the loss of more fertile top soil.",
