        "impacts": "Biodiversity loss is detrimental to well-functioning ecosystems and impacts on the overall health of the natural environment and the communities that depend on it. Biodiversity underpins ecosystem services that are essential for both people and nature such as water quality, pollination, commercial and community food growing and air quality. As such, biodiversity loss impacts on all aspects of society including individuals, communities and businesses that are reliant on ecosystem services e.g. agriculture. There is also increasing evidence of the benefits of biodiversity and connection with nature to human health and wellbeing, as well as wider community cohesion and installing a sense of pride. \\n\\nThe BHCC CRVA and action plan (2023) focuses on biodiversity loss and how to conserve and enhance biodiversity. This is complemented by the City Downland Estate Plan (2023) that provides guidance and a route map on managing the Downland estate through actions to reduce and store carbon through natural processes, enhance wildlife, improve public access and encouraging sustainable, local food production. On a wider scale, the emerging Local Nature Recovery Strategy (LNRS) due for publication in Spring 2026, will highlight measures and opportunities for improving nature and habitats across the East Sussex and Brighton & Hove area.\\n\\nChanges in climate such as hotter and drier summers, alongside changes in water availability and recharge of our chalk aquifer present a significant risk to species and ecosystem services. We are already seeing declines in species populations, local extinctions, species range modifications, impacts on migratory patterns and increases/changes in presence of pests and invasive species. Sea level rise is also a notable emerging risk for Brighton's natural environment. It could lead to saltwater intrusion of Brighton's chalk aquifer, due to hydrological connectivity with the sea. This can have cascading impacts for the natural environment which is reliant on the freshwater provided by the aquifer. In addition, rising sea levels could result in the loss of rare coastal habitats such as the city's iconic shingle coastline.\\n\\n\u2022\\twww.brighton-hove.gov.uk/net-zero/net-zero-what-were-doing\\n\u2022\\twww.brighton-hove.gov.uk/planning/planning-policy/city-downland-estate\\n\u2022\\twww.sussexnaturerecovery.org.uk\\n",
