        "impacts": "Storms are identified as a significant and recurring climate hazard in Cardiff, with increasing socio-economic impacts. The city has experienced multiple named storms in recent years, including Storm Darragh (2024), Storm Eunice (2022), and Storm Dennis (2020), each causing widespread disruption. Impacts have included power outages, transport cancellations, school and park closures, and extensive damage to infrastructure and property.\\n\\nCurrent:\\nThe coastal defences are in poor state of repair and therefore storm surges and sea level rise are starting to cause erosion to landfill site and potential environmental impact to Severn Estuary. \\n\\nAreas like Ely, Splott, and Butetown - which have high concentrations of ethnic minorities and lower-income households - are among the most socially vulnerable to flooding and storm damage. These communities often live in older housing stock, more prone to damage from high winds and rain.\\n\\nFuture:\\nStorm surges have the potential to cause flooding to gypsy traveller site and displacement of Cardiff Gypsy population.",
