        "sectorsExposed": "Human health and social work activities|Education|Water supply",
        "impacts": "Extreme heat poses growing risks to elderly people, children, and vulnerable health groups in Cardiff, both now and in the future. These risks are expected to intensify due to climate change, with hotter summers and more frequent heatwaves projected across the city.\\n\\nCurrent:\\nOlder adults (14% of Cardiff's population) are more susceptible to heat-related illnesses such as heatstroke, dehydration, and cardiovascular stress, whilst children, especially in schools without adequate ventilation or cooling, are vulnerable to overheating and fatigue. Furthermore, people with pre-existing health conditions (e.g. respiratory or cardiovascular diseases) face increased risks during hot weather.\\n\\nMany homes, care facilities, and schools in Cardiff are not designed to cope with high temperatures. Care homes and hospitals are identified as key vulnerability hotspots in the Cardiff Climate Risk Assessment.\\n\\nFlats and social housing - often occupied by lower-income or vulnerable residents - are particularly prone to overheating. Poor insulation and lack of ventilation exacerbate indoor heat stress.\\n\\nFuture:\\nBy the 2050s, Cardiff is projected to experience an increase of hot weather days and posing serious risks to elderly people, children, and those with health vulnerabilities:\\n- 22 summer days annually with temperatures above 25\u00b0C\\n- 4 hot summer days above 30\u00b0C\\n- Up to 7 tropical nights (minimum temperature > 20\u00b0C)\\n\\nHeat-related deaths in the UK are projected to triple by the 2050s. Vulnerable groups will be disproportionately affected, especially those in poorly ventilated buildings or without access to cooling.",
