        "refId": "Mitigation Action 5",
        "sector": "Transportation: Improve fuel economy and reduce CO2 emissions from aviation",
        "description": "Manchester Airport's Net Zero Commitments and Progress\\nManchester Airport is committed to achieving net-zero carbon emissions from its own operations by 2038. Since 2016, it has held Level 3+ carbon neutral status under the Airports Council International (ACI) Airport Carbon Accreditation programme, becoming the first UK airport to reach this level. The airport has reduced its Scope 1 and 2 emissions by 88% from a 2007/08 baseline, offsetting remaining emissions with Gold Standard carbon credits.\\n\\nKey decarbonisation initiatives include energy efficiency measures, such as the UK's first runway LED lighting and a new Terminal 2 facility, which is 15% more energy efficient than its predecessor. In 2021/22, 56% of the airport's energy came from renewable sources. Additional goals include operating all infrastructure on renewable energy by 2030, with new infrastructure powered by renewables from 2025 and a fully ultra-low emission vehicle fleet by 2030.\\n\\nIndustry Leadership and Sustainable Fuel\\nIn 2021, Manchester Airports Group (MAG) signed an MoU with Fulcrum BioEnergy to become the first UK airport with a direct supply pipeline of sustainable aviation fuel (SAF) by 2026. This initiative could create up to 1,500 green jobs and contribute \u00a3219 million to the regional economy. MAG is also one of two airport operators on the UK Government's Jet Zero Council and a founding member of Sustainable Aviation.\\n\\nMAG's role in advancing decarbonisation extends to hydrogen integration for future operations, using Manchester Airport as a test site to assess hydrogen use in aircraft taxiing, refuelling, and safety.\\n\\nCertifications and Sustainability Standards\\nMAG aims for ISO 50001 energy management certification and has achieved ISO 14001 certification in environmental management. New sustainable transport targets are set to reduce emissions from passenger and staff travel.\\n\\nAchievements and Recognition\\nMAG was the first airport operator to be named a Financial Times European Climate Leader two consecutive years (2021 and 2022).\\n\\nhttps://assets.live.dxp.maginfrastructure.com/f/73114/x/eb4273800d/mag-net-zero-carbon-roadmap-june-2024.pdf\\nhttps://www.magairports.com/work-with-us/our-sustainability-plans/climate-change-reporting/",
