        "sector": "Stationary energy: Energy efficiency/ retrofit measures addressing existing commercial, residential and/or municipal buildings",
        "description": "Manchester City Council (MCC) has implemented several key projects across various retrofit and decarbonisation initiatives aimed at mitigating climate change through significant carbon savings.\\nSocial Housing Decarbonisation Fund (SHDF): MCC has secured \u00a35 million of funding to improve over 700 council-owned social housing properties. Full scheme delivery anticipated to complete during 2026. This initiative focuses on enhancing energy efficiency through insulation upgrades, heating system improvements, and renewable energy integration. It is estimated that the retrofitting of these properties will save approximately 1,600-2,000 tonnes of CO2 annually by reducing energy consumption and reliance on fossil fuels.\\nPublic Sector Decarbonisation: Between 2020 and 2025, 40 operational council buildings have had retrofit works, including the installation of solar photovoltaics (PV) panels, air and ground source heat pumps and the replacement of lights to LEDs to make them more energy efficient. These measures, combined with the decarbonisation of the UK National Grid, have saved 32,637 tonnes of carbon over the five year period. The Council has developed a 'Roadmap' to zero carbon emissions from its operational buildings by 2038, aligning retrofit works with planned maintenance and 'end of life' replacement of gas boilers with a low carbon heating system.\\nFuture Public Building Retrofits: MCC has committed an additional c. \u00a310 million of its own funding to complete full retrofit of 7 more public buildings in 2025-6.\\n",
