        "refId": "Mitigation Action 17",
        "sector": "Stationary energy: Energy efficiency/ retrofit measures addressing existing commercial, residential and/or municipal buildings",
        "description": "The MCC Estates Carbon Reduction Programme is a programme to significantly improve the energy efficiency of 13 key Manchester City Council (MCC) buildings. Buildings in MCC's operational estate represented 68.9% of MCC's direct carbon dioxide emissions in 2018/19. The Carbon Reduction Programme will invest in schemes such as combined heat and power, solar photovoltaic panels, and the use of LED lighting within MCC's estate. The programme has secured \u00a339million to date and is expected to deliver 3668tCO2 per annum and install 2.5m.w of renewable capacity. Emissions from the operational estate have reduced by 7,086 Tonnes CO2 (30%) to the end of last financial year from the 2018/19 baseline A range of different measures have been installed across the buildings, based on the findings of detailed energy audits. They include 9,000 LED light fittings, building management systems, pipework insulation and a pool cover. Nine buildings have also had renewable energy generation capacity installed via solar panels. The second phase of the Zero Carbon Estate Programme involved a bid to the national Public Sector Decarbonisation Scheme (PSDS). Working with partners in the Greater Manchester Combined Authority (GMCA), MCC successfully secured \u00a318.2m of funding from the PSDS to invest in a range of heat decarbonisation, energy efficiency and generation projects with associated savings of 1,700 tCO2 per annum. Complex projects across 11 buildings were completed in 2021/22, Leisure Centres were a key part of the bid as they are some of the council's most energy intensive buildings. The technologies included in this phase of work include air source or ground source heat pumps, solar panels, and battery storage systems. The projects covered Wythenshawe Forum; East Manchester Leisure Centre; Hough End Leisure Centre; Arcadia Sports Centre; Moss Side Leisure Centre; North City Family and Fitness Centre; Manchester Aquatic Centre; The National Cycling Centre; Space Studios; The Sharp Project; and Zion Arts Centre. In April 2022, working with GMCA, the Council Was successful in a bid to PSDS for Round 3a funding. The bid was for \u00a33.1m of grant funding and included heat decarbonisation, energy efficiency and low carbon energy generation for eight buildings, including: Arbeta (Manchester Creative Digital Assets), Harpurhey District Office, Denmark Road Active Lifestyle Centre, Claremont Resource Centre, Didsbury Library, Hall Lane Resource Centre, and The Place at Platt Lane. The total carbon saving associated is 510 tCO2 a year. The programme has submitted a third bid for PSDS funding (for Round 3b) and is awaiting a decision currently for \u00a31.2m grant funding (with \u00a31m MCC funding) to support energy efficiency projects at the Town Hall Extension and Woodhouse Park Active Lifestyle Centre. The total carbon saving associated with these works is forecast to be around 650 tCO2 p.a.https://democracy.manchester.gov.uk/documents/s22754/MCC%20Climate%20Change%20Action%20Plan%202020-25.pdf https://democracy.manchester.gov.uk/documents/g3976/Public%20reports%20pack%2011th-Nov-2021%2010.00%20Environment%20and%20Climate%20Change%20Scrutiny%20Committee.pdf?T=10",
