        "hazard": "Extreme heat",
        "vulnerableGroups": "Elderly|Vulnerable health groups|Low-income households|Children and youth|Outdoor workers",
        "sectorsExposed": "Human health and social work activities|Construction|Agriculture|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply|Conservation|Water supply|Transportation and storage",
        "impacts": "The high temperatures observed recently represent risks to risks to health and wellbeing from high temperatures, particularly amongst the vulnerable; risks to productivity due to overheating in places of work; financial markets; risks food security and risks to infrastructure. Extreme heat has the potential to exacerbate health outcomes for populations such as children, the elderly and are vulnerable health groups due to the effects of heat stress. Moreover, heatwaves and extreme heat may also impact food security, further impacting vulnerable populations, including low-income households. Another concern within the risk to building fabrics is unusually high heat. July 2022 saw temperatures of nearly 40\u00b0C in York and has raised questions about the threat of fires due to the increased dryness during the summer months. Much of York's building stock was not designed to accommodate such temperatures (which could impact vulnerable groups such as the elderly in care homes), nor to deal with the increased threat of fires.High temperatures can also impact building foundations which can lead to subsidence, especially if the building is constructed on clay soil, which represents much of York's soilscape. Much of the land around York is classified as grade 2 or 3 conditions suitable for high quality arable crops (such as wheat, barley, oilseed rape etc.) and horticultural crops, making the impact of extreme heat to crops and soil a threat for socio-economic health and food security. This will impact York's residents and the agricultural sector in York whose arable crops will be at risk, causing financial impact. Impacts to the transportation sector are also becoming increasingly visible, with damage to road surfaces, vehicle overheating, buckled railway lines and sagging overhead cables along rail infrastructure all becoming potential future risks. Damage to public transport infrastructure would further exacerbate impacts on vulnerable groups, particularly children, the elderly and low-income households.",
