        "impacts": "The most vulnerable groups within biodiversity and habitat loss is of insects - Half of our 27 bumblebee species are in decline- Three of these bumblebee species have already gone extinct- Two-thirds of our moths are in long term decline- Across Europe 38% of bee and hoverfly species are in decline- 71% of our butterflies are in declineWith the reduction of these species it also provides problems for the human population as insect pollination is estimated to add value of \u00a3691 million to the UK economy annually. Without pollinators we would struggle to grow many vegetables and fruits including apples, pears, strawberries, beans and peas. As well as increasing biodiversity, creating more areas for plants/green spaces enables carbon capture, improves health and wellbeing and creates enhanced active travel networks, new green jobs, education, skills and volunteering opportunities. Availability of food and good nutrition is key to human health and will be threatened by food insecurity due to habitat destruction and biodiversity loss. This will impact children, low-income households and the elderly in particular. Biodiversity upholds ecosystem services which are vital for key sectors such as forestry, agriculture and conservation. Without biodiverse ecosystems, these sectors would decline rapidly causing a host of socio-economic impacts alongside the environmental decline. (2.2.5) Proportion of the population exposed to the hazard",
