        "sectorsExposed": "Conservation|Agriculture|Forestry",
        "impacts": "Soil health is critical for maintaining biodiversity, regulating water flows, ensuring water quality, recycling nutrients and providing multiple ecosystem services notably for agricultural and forestry production. Seasonal aridity in York is also catastrophic for soil health. York is on the Eastern side of the UK and is therefore likely to experience less rainfall than other parts of the country. On the other hand, the flash flooding that York experiences also has major impacts on soil health, for instance through the waterlogging of land. Much of the land around York is classified as grade 2 or 3 conditions suitable for high quality arable crops (such as wheat, barley, oilseed rape etc.) and horticultural crops, making the impact of soil degradation in these areas a cause for concern in terms of the socioeconomic effects in agriculture and food security. Impact to the agricultural and forestry sectors will have a knock-on effect to outdoor workers in these sectors. Subsequent impacts on food security will affect vulnerable populations particularly low-income households who may already be facing food insecurity.",
