        "sector": "Waste: Implement practices and policies to promote circular economy",
        "description": "Circular Economy Investment Case Research it is estimated that the benefits of moving towards a circular economy equate to a potential value of\\n\u00a33 billion per year in York and North Yorkshire. Across 15 specific opportunities evaluated, the research estimated CO2e savings of 650 kt/y, value generated of over \u00a3300m/y and the permanent creation of over 1,800 jobs. This carbon saving is over the region, not York specifically. https://edemocracy.northyorks.gov.uk/documents/s16032/Appendix%201%20-%20York%20and%20North%20Yorkshires%20Routemap%20to%20Carbon%20Negative.pdf \\nAccompanying investment was around \u00a3240m in total.Creating a circular network in York is key; moving towards a 'circular' approach means prioritizing a reduction in the amount of waste produced; with an emphasis on reuse,recycling, and repurposing materials as much as possible. A circular approach reduces both direct and indirect emissions but alsocreates economic opportunities. As such, moving towards a circular economy is one of the 32 objectives highlighted by our Climate Change Strategy (Objective 4.3: https://www.york.gov.uk/downloads/file/8948/york-climate-change-strategy-2022-to-2032) . KPIs for the Circular York include: reducing the number of single use plastics, increasing the number of venues and events with circular practices, increase sharing schemes in York, increase composting and reducing food waste. These KPIs amongst others will promote the circular economy in York and foster a variety of social, economic and environmental benefits. The Climate Change Strategy highlights steps towards a Circular Economy in York through initiatives such as the Real Junk Food Project and York Gin. The development of a Circular Towns Network in York will further facilitate businesses in engaging with circular practices and principles. Working with the York and North Yorkshire Local Enterprise Partnership, York will join other circular towns, such as Circular Malton, to embed circular economy principles into practices. Moving towards a circular economy in Yorkshire is an immense challenge. It requires unprecedented collaboration across a diverse range of stakeholders and supply chains, a substantial amount of investment and sufficient scale to achieve circular systems. As such joining a network such as Circular towns facilitates collaboration across the region and a joined-up approach to the circular economy.",
