        "sectorsExposed": "Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Conservation|Administrative and support service activities|Human health and social work activities|Water supply|Waste management|Fishing|Agriculture|Construction",
        "impacts": "Climate change is expected to significantly increase the risk of intense and unpredictable rainfall and therefore increase the flooding risk to our riverland communities. Cornwall has a number of rivers including the Camel, Gannel and Hayle rivers on the north coast and the Fal, Helford, Fowey and Tamar. This is likely to increase risk of flooding in some of our most populated communities including Truro, Falmouth, Launceston, Redruth, Hale and Helston. River flooding is indiscriminate and is therefore likely to affect all communities including vulnerable people. \\n\\nFlooding triggers increased pressure on emergency response services and is a public health risk. Short term flooding associated with heavy rainfall in river catchments or from storm surges at the coast come with a range of profound impacts of health and wellbeing over the short and long term. Flooding presents a threat to property and communities, with the potential for both immediate and long-term damage including structural damage from the force of water, subsidence and persistent damp. Loss of habitat condition due to climate stressors and lower arable and grassland production in low-lying and coastal areas. More river flooding events, and high impact summer flooding could lead to limited access to goods and services impacting business productivity. The elderly population are vulnerable due to the higher likelihood of frailty and ill-health. Children can be displaced from their homes causing anxiety, very young children would be more vulnerable as they are reliant on others. People with disabilities may have difficulty evacuating their homes in the event of a flood and may need assistance with personal care. Low income households may not be able to afford to repair damage and may not have access to flood insurance. \\n\\nSome of the most vulnerable sectors include:\\nAgriculture: Flooding can damage crops and livestock, which can lead to financial losses for farmers.\\nTourism: Flooding can damage tourist attractions, which can lead to a decline in tourism revenue.\\nTransport: Flooding can damage roads, railways, and airports, which can disrupt travel and commerce. \\n\\nA full flood risk profile can be found at https://map.cornwall.gov.uk/website/ccmap/index.html zoomlevel=4&xcoord=182920&ycoord=42857&wsName=sfra&layerName=Functional%20floodplain%203B:Flood%20zone%203:Flood%20zone%202",
