        "impacts": "Older people: Older people are more likely to be affected by storms, as they are more likely to live in coastal areas and have health conditions that make them more vulnerable to the effects of extreme weather. \\n\\nLow-income households: Low-income households are more likely to live in areas that are at risk of flooding or coastal erosion, and they may not have the resources to adapt to the impacts of climate change.\\n\\nPeople with disabilities: People with disabilities may have difficulty evacuating their homes during a storm, and they may also be more vulnerable to the effects of extreme weather, such as flooding or power outages.\\n\\nFarmers: Farmers are particularly vulnerable to the impacts of climate change, as they rely on the weather for their livelihoods. Storms can damage crops, livestock, and infrastructure, and they can also lead to flooding, which can destroy crops and homes.\\n\\nFishermen: Fishermen are also vulnerable to the impacts of climate change, as they rely on the ocean for their livelihoods. Storms can damage fishing boats and equipment, and they can also lead to changes in fish populations, which can make it more difficult to catch fish.\\n\\nThe increase in storms is a serious threat to Cornwall. The county is already vulnerable to flooding, with an exposed coastline, and the rise in sea levels is only going to make this problem worse. Storms can also cause damage to property and infrastructure, disrupt business and tourism and they can even be deadly.\\n\\nIn recent years, Cornwall has experienced a number of severe storms, including Storm Arwen, Storm Eunice, and Storm Franklin. These storms have caused widespread damage, with roofs blown off houses, trees uprooted, and power lines brought down. In some cases, flooding has forced people to evacuate their homes.",
