        "impacts": "Increased risk of wildfires: Climate change is expected to lead to warmer and drier weather conditions, which will create a more favourable environment for wildfires. This is a particular concern for Cornwall, which is already prone to wildfires due to its dry climate and abundance of vegetation. \\n\\nIncreased severity of wildfires: Climate change is also expected to lead to more severe wildfires. This is because warmer temperatures will increase the rate of fire spread, while drier conditions will make it more difficult to extinguish fires.\\n\\nIncreased health risks: Wildfires can release harmful pollutants into the air, which can pose a health risk to people who are exposed to them. These pollutants can cause respiratory problems, such as asthma and bronchitis, and can even lead to death.\\n\\nEconomic disruption: Wildfires can cause significant economic disruption. They can damage property, businesses, and infrastructure. They can also lead to the loss of jobs and tourism revenue.\\n\\nThe most vulnerable populations to the impacts of wildfires in Cornwall are the elderly, the young, and those with respiratory problems. These populations are more likely to be affected by the health risks associated with wildfires, and they may also be less able to evacuate their homes in the event of a wildfire.\\n\\nThe most vulnerable sectors to the impacts of wildfires in Cornwall are the tourism industry, the agricultural sector, and the forestry sector. These sectors are all reliant on the natural environment, and they can suffer significant losses in the event of a wildfire.\\n\\nIt is important to note that the impacts of climate change on wildfires in Cornwall are still uncertain. However, it is clear that climate change is likely to make wildfires more frequent, more severe, and more harmful. This is a serious threat to the people and economy of Cornwall, and it is important to take steps to mitigate the risks.\\n\\nIn 2022, the number of wildfires in Cornwall increased by 80% compared with the previous year and there were on average almost two wildfires per week.",
