      {
        "planType": "Standalone adaptation plan",
        "planName": "Dundee Biodiversity Action Plan 2020-2030:\\n\\nhttps://www.dundeecity.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/dundees_biodiversity_action_plan_2020-2030.pdf",
        "yearAdopted": null,
        "scope": "Same (jurisdiction-wide) - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "sectors": "Update: Updates to the plan are published every 3-5 years",
        "renewableTarget": "Dundee's Biodiversity Action Plan 2020-2030 is shaped by the city's recognition of the climate emergency and the interdependence between biodiversity and climate resilience. The plan acknowledges that climate change is a major driver of biodiversity loss, but also highlights how healthy ecosystems contribute to climate mitigation and adaptation. This dual role of biodiversity\u2014as both vulnerable to and protective against climate impacts\u2014is central to the plan's strategic approach. It positions biodiversity enhancement as a key component of Dundee's broader Climate Action Plan, aiming to build ecological resilience through better planning, habitat connectivity, and green infrastructure.\\n\\nClimate scenarios have informed the plan's emphasis on creating a resilient urban environment. For example, the strategy promotes the expansion and connection of species-rich greenspaces to buffer against climate-related stresses such as extreme weather and habitat fragmentation. It also integrates biodiversity considerations into local development frameworks, ensuring that future urban growth supports ecological sustainability. By aligning with national and international biodiversity targets\u2014such as the Aichi Targets and Scotland's post-2020 biodiversity framework\u2014the plan ensures that Dundee's local actions contribute meaningfully to global climate and biodiversity goals.",
        "emissionsTarget": "Relevant department within jurisdiction"
      },
      {
        "planType": "Standalone energy-related plan",
        "planName": "Dundee Local heat and Energy Efficiency Delivery Plan 2024-2028\\n\\nThe plan in linked here: https://www.dundeecity.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/final_lhees_delivery_plan_18.11.24.pdf",
        "yearAdopted": null,
        "scope": "Same (jurisdiction-wide) - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "sectors": "Update: Updates to the plan are published every 3-5 years|Monitoring: Information on progress of plan is monitored and publicly reported every 5+ years|Evaluation: Evaluation of plan takes place every 5+ years",
        "renewableTarget": "The Dundee Local Heat and Energy Efficiency Strategy (LHEES) Delivery Plan has been shaped by an understanding of climate scenarios in several key ways:\\n\\n1. Alignment with Net Zero and Climate Emergency Goals\\nThe LHEES is explicitly designed to support Dundee's response to the climate emergency and its commitment to achieving net zero emissions. Climate scenarios\u2014particularly those projecting future emissions pathways and temperature increases\u2014have informed the urgency and scale of interventions proposed in the plan.\\n\\n2. Heat Decarbonisation and Energy Efficiency\\nThe strategy prioritises heat decarbonisation and improved energy efficiency in buildings, which are central to mitigating climate impacts. These priorities reflect scenario-based modelling that shows the need to transition away from fossil fuels and reduce energy demand to meet long-term climate targets.\\n\\n3. Health and Wellbeing Co-benefits\\nClimate scenarios often highlight increased risks to public health due to extreme weather and poor air quality. The LHEES responds to these risks by aiming to improve thermal comfort and indoor air quality, thereby enhancing residents' health and wellbeing.\\n\\n4. Fuel Poverty and Economic Resilience\\nUnderstanding future climate risks also informs the plan's focus on alleviating fuel poverty and creating economic opportunities. By improving building performance and supporting local energy systems, the strategy aims to build resilience against energy price volatility and climate-related economic shocks.",
        "emissionsTarget": "Relevant department within jurisdiction|Consultant|Dedicated team within jurisdiction"
      },
      {
        "planType": "Standalone energy-related plan",
        "planName": "Dundee Energy Efficiency and Net Zero Strategy 2023-2027\\n\\nThe plan is linked here: https://www.dundeecity.gov.uk/sites/default/files/draft_344-2023_-_energy_efficiency_and_net_zero_strategy_2023-2027_full_rpt.pdf",
        "yearAdopted": null,
        "scope": "Same (jurisdiction-wide) - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "sectors": "Other: To be reviewed and updated regularly to ensure it remains aligned with evolving national policy, funding opportunities, and technological developments. Specific review frequency not explicitly stated, but embedded in broader strategies.",
        "renewableTarget": "The Dundee City Council Energy Efficiency and Net Zero Strategy 2023-2027 is shaped by national climate legislation and long-term decarbonisation scenarios, particularly Scotland's statutory commitment to net zero emissions by 2045. The strategy aligns with the Council's broader climate response, including the Net Zero Transition Plan and the Local Heat and Energy Efficiency Strategy (LHEES), and is informed by the Climate Change (Scotland) Act 2009 (as amended), the Heat in Buildings Strategy, and the Fuel Poverty Act. These frameworks provide the emissions reduction targets and energy performance standards that underpin the strategy's goals, such as achieving EPC Band B across the housing stock by 2032.\\n\\nIt adopts a \u201cfabric-first\u201d principle, aiming to improve building insulation and energy efficiency before deploying low-carbon technologies like heat pumps or PV systems. While the strategy acknowledges uncertainties\u2014such as the ongoing review of EESSH2 and evolving standards for new builds\u2014it remains grounded in the assumption that climate-driven regulatory tightening will continue. This forward-looking stance ensures that Dundee's housing stock is progressively aligned with future climate resilience and emissions reduction requirements.",
        "emissionsTarget": "Dedicated team within jurisdiction"
      }
