        "vulnerableGroups": "Marginalized/minority communities|Low-income households",
        "sectorsExposed": "Conservation|Arts, entertainment and recreation|Forestry|Agriculture|Fishing",
        "impacts": "The Essex coastline is known for its varied biodiversity, including numerous bird species and seals. The coastline sustains numerous coastal communities as well as shellfisheries. . A diverse range of climate hazards impact the natural environment leading to potential biodiversity loss. The Adaptation Plan Framework developed by Essex County Council in 2024 illustrates the following risks: \u2022 Overheating, coupled with periods of drought, can lead to habitat degradation in all urban habitats but especially wetlands and rivers. \u2022 risk of habitat failures due to pollution, and loss of soil and habitat as these are washed away in events of surface water flooding. \u2022 Pollution from historic inland landfills: Due to the effects of climate change, including ground water level variations, as well as both increased surface water in some areas, and lack of surface water in others, there is a risk of increased levels of gas and leachate polluting the environment at historic inland landfill sites across Essex. the potential impacts of this include: the killing of vegetation and crops (resulting in fines); underground fires; increased release of powerful greenhouse gases; and the contamination of ground and surface water. \u2022 Reduced rainfall with periods of drought, can lead to habitat degradation in all habitats but especially wetlands and rivers. \u2022 Due to extreme weather events there are risks of habitat failure or degradation; and risk of significant coastal erosion. \u2022 Subsidence investigations regularly lead to felling of nearby trees due to often unsubstantiated claims that the tree roots are affect the building foundations. \u2022 Coastal erosion and flooding present risks to designated freshwater habitats behind sea walls. Many habitats behind the seawall are designated and their loss may lead to a requirement for replacement elsewhere or fines. \u2022 Breach of waste filled sea wall as a result of climate change include rising sea levels, coastal erosion and storm surges. This poses the risk of a full breach of a sea wall or flood defence, causing potentially hazardous waste to enter the sea. The impact on any breach could encompass polluting the biosphere and flora and fauna, as well as potential financial penalties due to damage to protected fisheries and huge reputational damage to ECC.",
