        "impacts": "Extreme weather events contribute to soil degradation and erosion. This impacts the environment through an increase in desertification, loss of fertile land, loss of natural green infrastructure and biodiversity, and an increase in pollution and sedimentation in streams and rivers, carrying soil pollution from farmland, clogging these waterways and causing declines in fish and other species. Eroded soils don't easily retain water, increasing the risk of flooding and landslides for vulnerable communities, coastal erosion, and river erosion. This combination of climate-related hazards cause damages to assets such as farmland, infrastructure, residences, schools, business sites and historic sites, especially for those located in the most deprived areas of the county, both rural and coastal communities. ( https://www.bgs.ac.uk/news/river-erosion-the-forgotten-hazard-of-flooding/#:~:text=Infrastructure%20damage&text=This%20makes%20river%20scour%20extremely,flood%20defences%20and%20electricity%20pylons.) Soil degradation and erosion impacts the Essex economy by reducing farm productivity, impacting food security and damaging ecosystem services, such as the availability of freshwater. \\n\\nDry weather, high temperatures, prolonged heat and prolonged wet are major factors in the emergence of shrink-swell subsidence: Essex is one of the areas most affected by subsidence as its clay soil is vulnerable to losing moisture, leading to ground cracking and shrinking, causing damage to buildings and roads. (https://www.essex.gov.uk/sites/default/files/migration_data/files/downloads.ctfassets.net/knkzaf64jx5x/217WfZa7CrcOT75C9zO9UB/5b4f5ba37be34abe42935ac49a0b4637/Essex_Green_Infrastructure_strategy.pdf ) Subsidence can potentially lead to financial losses for property owners, expensive remedial work, increased insurance premiums, lower house prices and impacts on infrastructure such as transport and utility pipes. ( https://www.bgs.ac.uk/datasets/geoclimate-ukcp09-and-ukcp18/ )",
