        "impacts": "Vulnerability to coastal flooding is increasing as the Essex coastline is eroding rapidly. In 2025 the latest NAFRA2 data shows there are 65,571 properties at risk from river and sea flooding, equal to 10% of all households in Essex. This is a 65% increase since 2022. (https://environment.data.gov.uk/dataset/dcbad548-ba75-4f32-bf22-306f9059343e)\\n\u2022 UK sea levels have risen 19.5cm since 1901 with the last three years the highest on record for annual mean sea level. UK sea level rise is accelerating and is now happening faster than the global average. (State of the UK Cllimate 2024, https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/research/climate/maps-and-data/about/state-of-climate). \u2022 A 2023 briefing note by the University of East Anglia and the Tyndall Centre for Climate Change Research described the East of England as the UK's most vulnerable region in terms of the potential impacts of climate change. Around 20% of the region is below sea-level and, in some areas, up to 25% of properties are at risk of flooding. (ECC, Climate Adaptation Plan Framework, 2024) By their nature, coastal communities are vulnerable to various natural hazards, including coastal erosion, which also poses a threat to agricultural and recreational land (Essex Rural Strategy, 2016-2020). \u2022 UK sea levels will continue to rise well beyond 2100 under all future emissions scenarios, (https://www.metoffice.gov.uk/research/news/2019/uk-sea-level-projections-to-2300) \u2022 Coastal flooding impacts, including sea level rise, will disproportionately affect people living in deprived areas along the coast. A 2021 study commissioned by ECC found significant levels of community need in coastal areas. For example, communities along the Tendring coast (e.g. Clacton, Walton and Harwich) face particular challenges regarding their connectedness to economic and social opportunities. The review also identified areas in Essex categorised as 'left behind'; that is, they exhibit both high levels of deprivation and community need (being within the most deprived 10% of wards in England on both the Indices of Deprivation 2019 and the Essex Community Needs Index). Twelve wards in Essex were identified as being 'left behind', of which eight are coastal towns (Clacton and Tendring).",
