        "impacts": "\u2022 East Anglia is one of the driest regions in the UK, with droughts and water scarcity projected to increase due to climate change. In 2022, the East of England was officially declared to be in drought by Central Government. High temperatures and little rainfall led to one of the driest summers for Essex and the county experienced a heatwave with record breaking temperatures. The prolonged dry weather generated intense wildfires across Essex in August 2022, including a large fire on Canvey Island (an area with high deprivation and health inequalities). (https://www.gov.uk/government/news/action-taken-following-dry-conditions-in-suffolk-norfolk-and-essex) \u2022 The agricultural sector is a major part of Essex economy, over 61% of the county is agricultural land. Drought and extreme heat cause hazards to livestock, destroy fresh produce in fields, and force early harvesting creating difficulties for storing and selling goods. It also causes delays to the planting of new crops and damage to soil, increasing the costs of production and increasing the final price for consumers, with impacts on access to healthy food (particularly for vulnerable populations) and ultimately an mpacti on food security. there is a risk that farmers will be forced out of the industry by rising costs. Small businesses such as horticulture and landscaping are also impacted negatively by drought. (https://www.essex.gov.uk/sites/default/files/migration_data/files/downloads.ctfassets.net/knkzaf64jx5x/217WfZa7CrcOT75C9zO9UB/5b4f5ba37be34abe42935ac49a0b4637/Essex_Green_Infrastructure_strategy.pdf ; https://www.nwg.co.uk/globalassets/corporate/environment-pdfs/drought-plan/esw/esw-final-drought-plan-appendix---may-2022---published-version.pdf) \u2022 Prolonged periods of drought and lack of precipitation results in water shortages. Essex is a highly water stressed area, with water scarcity increasing. Water is essential for the economy to function, plays a vital role in sectors such as health, energy, and food production. (https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/water-stressed-areas-2021-classification) \u2022 Reduced rainfall with periods of drought, can lead to \\nhabitat degradation in all habitats but especially \\nwetlands and rivers (ECC, Adaptation Plan Framework, 2024)",
