        "sector": "Stationary energy: Requirements which incentivize net zero carbon, Passivhaus or other ultra-high-efficiency standards for new buildings",
        "description": "The action to ban gas heating systems in all new buildings within the city boundary from 1st April 2024 (action 42 of Glasgow's Climate Plan - https://glasgow.gov.uk/article/2389/Glasgow-s-Climate-Plan) has been superseded by the Scottish Government's 'New Build Heat Standard 2024' (https://www.gov.scot/publications/new-build-heat-standard-factsheet/) that has banned use of polluting systems in new build properties consented after 1st April 2024. \\n\\nOther key actions underway to reduce stationary energy consumption include the delivery of Glasgow's Local Heat and Energy Efficiency Strategy (LHEES) programme (www.glasgow.gov.uk/lhees) which is looking to:\\n(i) deploy large-scale heat networks as a mechanism of reducing heating based emissions, tackling fuel poverty and improving energy security and \\n(ii) exploring the potential of partnership delivery models between GCC and the private sector that could support the financing and delivery of Glasgow's Net Zero programme in line with local and national targets, focusing specifically on the rollout of heat networks at scale and pace.",
