        "refId": "Mitigation Action 10",
        "sector": "Stationary energy: Energy efficiency/ retrofit measures addressing existing commercial, residential and/or municipal buildings",
        "description": "Support provided through Retrofit Accelerator-Homes (RA-H) consisted of technical advice and support for social housing provider, to cut carbon and reduce energy bills through improving the energy efficiency of their homes. The Mayor's Retrofit Accelerator-Homes Innovation Partnership (RAH-IP) helped social landlords and UK building firms to work together to upgrade ageing homes in the capital. The scheme linked up housing providers and builders through all stages of home retrofitting, from planning through to large-scale delivery. This aimed to dramatically increase the pace of projects that upgrade cold, damp housing stock to homes fit for the future. Seven London boroughs were supported through RA-H to enter into contracts with building firms through the IP framework, to deliver the pipeline of over 1,800 whole house retrofits. Retrofit Accelerator-Homes Innovation Partnership (RAH-IP) included formalised contract and procurement tools and a business model which could enable finance of deep retrofit. It was structured to enable development of products and supply chain innovations through a four-stage process, which meant products and processes could be prototyped and piloted in small numbers before scaling, reducing risk for all parties and creating the space for innovation and learning. Installations through the RAH Innovation Partnership have varied across homes. and energy efficiency measures installed include solid wall insulation; roof insulation; solar PV panels; windows and external doors; heat pumps; battery storage; thermal storage; external wall insulation; mechanical ventilation; energy modules and heat recovery systems. This has been part of the necessary work to increase the quality and speed of retrofits, enabling social housing landlords to cut carbon emissions and reduce heating costs for thousands of homes and thus tackling the growing issue of fuel poverty. By 2025, 120 homes will be retrofitted. Works have resulted in 200 jobs being supported and \u00a324m has been committed through grant and match funding. Based on the 120 homes being retrofitted, it is estimated that there will be: \\n-\\tannual energy savings of \u00a31,512 per home \\n-\\t396 tonnes of carbon saved per year (3.3 tonnes per home) \\n-\\t638MWh of solar PV generation",
