        "impacts": "Toon Monsoon and Thunder Thursday, June 2012 - Flash flood event that overwhelmed the drainage networks and created extreme volumes of surface water flooding. Around 500 residential properties that were flooded internally and over 50 non-residential properties affected. Damages estimated at \u00a370-80m. There were a number of other extreme weather events in 2012 also. The frequency of extreme weather events causing flooding is expected to have risen already from 1 in 100 year to 1 in 40 year events, arising from:\\n\u2022 Banks bursting from the River Tyne\\n\u2022 Surface water and drainage flooding\\n\u2022 Coastal and tidal flooding. \\n\\nAn example of this on the vulnerable population such as the elderly in Newcastle 14.9% of the population is over 65 years in 2021. During heavy precipitation which causes flooding outs elderly people at risk as they may be less able to prepare for and cope during floods such as mobility issues, life support equipment failure, loss of access to medical care as flood events can directly impact local medical services due to infrastructure, such as roads being flooded. \\n\\nWe expect the intensity and frequency of these events to continue increasing as a result of climate change. The transportation sector is particular vulnerable to disruption caused by surface water flooding of strategic infrastructure.",
