        "refId": "Mitigation Action 3",
        "sector": "Transportation: Improve walking, cycling and integrated transit access",
        "description": "Local cycling and walking infrastructure plans are currently being developed alongside quantifiable carbon reduction targets, behavioural analysis and active travel campaigns, promoting cycling and walking to school and speed management protocols. The precise cost, carbon and energy savings figures are not currently known for these actions.\\n\\nAn example project is the Kildwick to Silsden Active Travel Link which received \u00a3972,048 from the York and North Yorkshire Combined Authority Net Zero Fund. The scheme upgraded 2 kms of towpath between Kildwick in Craven and Cowling swing bridge on the North Yorkshire/WYCA boundary. The towpath condition along this length of the Leeds and Liverpool canal was poor, the surface was muddy and uneven with large tree roots creating trip hazards. There was no safe alternative for people to walk, wheel and cycle between Kildwick and Silsden. The anticipated output from this scheme is the increase in cycle trips by 96% (135) and walking trips by 89% (629). Not only will the scheme provide increased accessibility for those in wheelchairs or using pushchairs but the scheme is also forecast to remove 50,000 car driven kilometres per year from the local network. Air quality will improve as a result of the scheme and a reduction in greenhouse gases emissions (CO2e) resulting from reduced vehicle km will save CO2 tonne equivalent of 101.04 tonnes over the 20-year appraisal period. Completion of this project will also lead to wider benefits such as improved health and wellbeing and an economic impact in terms of tourism and spend in the local economy. \\n\\nhttps://www.northyorks.gov.uk/roads-parking-and-travel/major-transport-schemes-and-plans/local-cycling-and-walking-infrastructure-plans-lcwips",
