        "sectorsExposed": "Human health and social work activities",
        "impacts": "Current heatwave risk as a function of vulnerability, exposure and hazard demonstrates high heatwave risk in Oxford City. Eight of the ten wards with the highest current heatwave risk in Oxfordshire County are located in Oxford City. Extreme heat can impact vulnerable groups which have a lower ability to adapt and the people at greatest risk from heat health impacts (morbidity and mortality), including: \u2022 Elderly people, chronically ill people and people taking certain medicines may have impairments in their thermoregulation, thus more likely to overheat. \u2022 Children under 5 years are unable to control their body temperatures as efficiently as adults and are more likely to overheat. \u2022 There is a link between increasing temperatures (resulting in dehydration) and increasing infections of Gram-negative bacteria, such as E. coli. (risk of such infectious diseases is greatest in elderly people). \u2022 People with alcohol or drug dependence and homeless people may be less able to adapt to extreme temperatures",
