        "impacts": "Exceptional rainfall in January 2024 saw the River Thames, which passes through Reading, reach its highest level since 1947 as a result of which flood conditions occurred, inundating 21 properties and 3 business premises. Reading experienced a major flood in 1947 when much of Lower Caversham was flooded. This flood was in part caused by snow melt across the Thames catchment but a flood of this size could also happen just from rainfall, as happened in 1894, when flood levels were even higher on the Thames. Flood modelling by the UK Environment Agency shows that over 700 properties are currently at risk of flooding from the River Thames in Caversham and north Reading area alone. With climate change this number will rise. This makes it the largest community at risk from the Thames without existing or proposed flood defences. Homes and businesses in low lying areas of Caversham flooded in 2014 and 2003. Houses were surrounded by floodwater and a number of roads were closed to vehicles. In 2003 several roads were closed, some for as long as 5 days. The wet winter of 2013/14 led to widespread flooding along Reading's waterways and floodplains (Thames, Loddon and Kennet). Sonning Bridge was closed on two occasions in January and for part of February, while Loddon Bridge Park & Ride was closed for much of January. In some areas, flooding due to rising groundwater levels was a problem and there was widespread travel disruption. Similarly, the wet period in late winter 2019-20 caused widespread travel disruption. January 2014 was the wettest January on record in Reading, with 151 mm of rail (251% the normal January rainfall). February 2014 was the wettest February on record in Reading, with 117 mm of rain (287 % of normal). Reading has also experienced recent summer flash flooding - in July 2007, 69 mm of rain fell in only 15 hours (the monthly mean rainfall for July in Reading is 46 mm), leading to flooding on many local rivers. The Reading Climate Change Adaptation Plan includes a summary of impact by area showing the potential spatial distribution of climate impacts on different parts of the Borough. We know from the UK Climate Projections that variability in rainfall is increasing. Wet winters will get wetter, but we can still expect some dry winters. Summer rainfall is expected to decrease significantly, but when it rains in summer there may be more intense rainfall events.",
