        "impacts": "Summer 1976 saw the culmination of a prolonged drought which had started in April 1975. July/August 1976 saw barely any rain for 37 days, making it the longest period without measurable rainfall. Reading is a growing town which will place further pressure on water resources at the same time that climate change will be having an impact on water availability and water quality. It is therefore expected that drought risk will increase in the coming decades. As well as impacts on people, drought will have impacts on Reading's natural environment. Reading Borough Council's Local Plan and Biodiversity Action Plan identify Biodiversity Opportunity Areas, one of which, Kennet Valley East, has been highlighted as an area where measures to retain winter flood water in the flood plain of the River Kennet throughout the year could have benefits for biodiversity and carbon storage. The Council is therefore engaged with local partners in a project to take this forward. \u00a320,000 has been allocated for a feasibility study. The first part of this study was completed in March 2024 and suggested significant potential, including income from Biodiversity Net Gain to fund ongoing maintenance, for a scheme.",
