        "sector": "Transportation: Electric vehicle charging points and infrastructure",
        "description": "The \u00a310m Local Electric Vehicle Infrastructure (LEVI) pilot fund is intended to encourage large scale, ambitious and commercially sustainable projects that leverage significant private sector investment to support the rollout of electric vehicle charging infrastructure. \\nSunderland secured \u00a3493,568 grant funding in March 2023 towards a \u00a3822,612.70 project supporting the delivery of 219 fast charging outlets for residents at Riverside Sunderland and on-street locations. This includes 115 wall-mounted charge-point sockets at Riverside Sunderland Multi-Storey Car Park as well as residential on-street charging / EV Community Hubs supporting 104 outlets at 20 locations across the city. Delivery of the Hubs is underway with up to 80 standard 7.1kW charge-points being delivered at 35 locations. The hubs will be complete at the end of 2025.\\n\\nThe Council is collaborating closely with the North-East Combined Authority as part of a regional project to deliver a phased programme of further charge-point infrastructure for residents and visitors over the next three years. The region has secured \u00a315.8m to invest in charging infrastructure. This is part of the governments next round of LEVI funding to help support the public's transition to electric cars. Objectives include:\\n\u2022\\tTo deliver a step-change in the deployment of local, primarily low power, on-street charging infrastructure across England.\\n\u2022\\tTo accelerate the commercialisation of, and investment in, the local charging infrastructure sector.\\nWork is underway to deliver up to 4 rapid charging stations to be located at destination sites across the city to provide short stay charging facilities for both residents and visitors at Seaburn seafront, the Coalfields and Washington.\\nFunding has also been secured to enable delivery of charge-points at destination and leisure related locations. Four locations in Sunderland include country parks and heritage sites to provide short stay top up charging for visitors. These charging hubs are awaiting install in 2025.",
