        "sectorsExposed": "Conservation|Water supply|Waste management|Agriculture|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities",
        "impacts": "With decreased precipitation already being experienced in the West Midlands during the summer in particular, there will be increased water scarcity, disproportionally impacting more deprived areas with greater pressure on health and care services. Increased water scarcity will also cause higher demand and raise water prices, affecting access for lower income households. As of early August 2025, the West Midlands, along with four other areas are considered to be in drought.",
        "populationExposed": "Data is not available",
