        "sectorsExposed": "Water supply|Accommodation and food service activities|Real estate activities|Transportation and storage|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Waste management|Human health and social work activities",
        "impacts": "The West Midlands flood risk is primarily from surface flooding and extreme rain events. As of 2017, the number of people in the West Midlands deemed to be living in an area of high surface flood risk, was 12,495. In addition, 25 services, (schools, hospitals, etc,), 1,101 non-residential properties, 38km of roads, and 18km of railway and 126 hectares of grade 1,2, and 3 agricultural land were also deemed to be at a high risk, demonstrating that flooding is a perennial threat. In future, it is plausible that extreme storm events could increase by as much as 40%, with winter precipitation predicted to increase by around 12%. This would also see a threefold increase in the likelihood of 'very wet days' (defined as more than 25mm in a 24 hour period). These are based on UK climate projections. This is likely to push many of those living under a current 'moderate risk' into a higher risk category. In the West Midlands, in winter, rainfall is expected to increase by approximately 6% by the 2050s and by between 9% to 14% by the 2080s from a 1981-2000 baseline, depending on global efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. Rapid rainfall can lead to damaging surface flooding. Flooding poses a risk to many aspects of society and infrastructure, including housing, schools, health infrastructure, transport infrastructure and waste services. A recent case study, economic analysis of the 2023 flash floods found that July 2023 was the UK's sixth wettest July on record, with an average rainfall of 120.4mm across England. One particularly severe period of heavy rain and thunderstorms affected the WMCA area on 8 and 9 July, where yellow weather warnings for thunderstorms were issued by the Met Office across the entire region from Wolverhampton, across the Black Country. and cities of Birmingham and Coventry. Roads were flooded across the WMCA area, with Birmingham suffering particularly badly. Businesses were reported to suffer from flooding during this period. The July 2023 flooding event resulted in 80 properties being flooded, with associated property damages. Whilst this was the largest cost of this event (2.5m), there were also economic (societal) impacts from the projected impacts of flooding on mental health (0.26m).\\n\\nThe WMCA are working with the University of Birmingham to develop its understanding of the lived experiences of urban flooding felt by the most vulnerable communities and wards in the region. This should enable to the WMCA to build its evidence base",
