        "impacts": "Drier ground conditions caused by higher summer temperatures and occurrences of drought. Increased intensity or duration of drought events may impact upon surface and groundwater levels and quality. Higher air & water temperatures lower dissolved oxygen levels and increase the concentration of pollutants. Changes in water temperature leading to increase in occurrence and risk from invasive or harmful waterborne species. Higher air & water temperatures combined with increased nutrient pollution causes an increased incidence of harmful algal blooms. Need for greater investment in water infrastructure to maintain the quality of the public water supply. Moorland and upland peatland habitats become dry, with an increase in wildfire index. Blanket, raised bog and valley-mire systems become drier. Impacts on grassland habitats due to greater incidence of drought. Impacts upon species diversity in hedgerows due to changes in climatic conditions and vulnerability of some species to temperature change. Impacts on woodland habitat due to greater incidence of drought and water deficit. Headwaters, streams and ponds may dry out due to drought conditions or experience changes in flow. The rivers are a major source of water abstraction for domestic and commercial uses. Changes in flow and alteration of hydrology may impact site conditions. Potential shift in species range due to changes in climatic conditions. Loss of habitat or ecological niche for species due to changing climatic conditions. Key historic assets may be vulnerable to damage. Soil shrinkage and dying out of substrates in areas that are prone to subsidence. Reduction in soil moisture content. Loss of archaeological deposits, damage to or loss of scheduled features or evidence. Key assets and infrastructure may be vulnerable to damage from heat. Increased pressure on the public water supply with the projected growth in development. Risk of damage to local energy infrastructure. Longer and more sustained periods of strong sunshine. Higher summer temperatures and Increased period of drought impacting on livestock farming. Lower summer yields of hay, silage and fodder crops during times of drought. Reduced precipitation and increased intensity and duration of drought may affect supply of water for agricultural use. Higher exterior temperatures and increased low level ozone formation and poorer air quality.",
